HEADWORD: Squat
<hw>Squat</hw> <pr>(skw⟦ocr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>The angel fish (<spn>Squatina angelus</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Squat
<hw>Squat</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Squatted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Squatting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>squatten</ets> to
crush, OF. <ets>esquater</ets>, <ets>esquatir</ets> (cf. It.
<ets>quatto</ets> squat, cowering), perhaps fr. L. <ets>ex</ets> +
<ets>coactus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>cogere</ets> to drive or urge
together. See <er>Cogent</er>, <er>Squash</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To sit down upon the hams or heels; <as>as, the savages
<ex>squatted</ex> near the fire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sit close to the ground; to cower; to stoop, or
lie close, to escape observation, as a partridge or rabbit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To settle on another's land without title; also, to
settle on common or public lands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Squat
<hw>Squat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To bruise or make flat by a
fall.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Squat
<hw>Squat</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Sitting on the hams or
heels; sitting close to the ground; cowering; crouching.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him there they found,⟦br⟧
<qex>Squat</qex> like a toad, close at the ear of Eve.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Short and thick, like the figure of an animal
squatting.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The round, <xex>squat</xex> turret.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>R. Browning.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The head [of the squill insect] is broad and <qex>squat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Squat
<hw>Squat</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The posture of one that
sits on his heels or hams, or close to the ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sudden or crushing fall.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small vein of
ore.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A mineral consisting of tin ore and
spar.</def> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au> <au>Woodward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Squat snipe</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
jacksnipe; -- called also <altname>squatter</altname>.</cd>
<mark>[Local, U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squaterole</ent>⟦br⟧
